"Van Vliet A.J.H., De Groot R.S., Bellens Y., Braun P., Bruegger R., Bruns E., Clevers J., Estreguil C., Flechsig M., Jeanneret F., Maggi M., Martens P., Menne B., Menzel A., Sparks T.","The European Phenology Network",2003,"International Journal of Biometeorology","47","4",,"202","212",,,10.1007/s00484-003-0174-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0141723339&partnerID=40&md5=4ce82a8d26d09f25b58d9e5ef54ead2e","Environmental Systems Analysis Group, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 8080, 6700 DD, Wageningen, Netherlands; Centre for Geoinformation, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Inst. for Environ./Sustainability, Joint Research Centre, European Commission, Ispra, Italy; Lehrstuhl fuer Bioklimatologie, Technical University Munich, Munich, Germany","Van Vliet, A.J.H., Environmental Systems Analysis Group, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 8080, 6700 DD, Wageningen, Netherlands; De Groot, R.S., Environmental Systems Analysis Group, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 8080, 6700 DD, Wageningen, Netherlands; Bellens, Y.; Braun, P.; Bruegger, R.; Bruns, E.; Clevers, J., Centre for Geoinformation, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Estreguil, C., Inst. for Environ./Sustainability, Joint Research Centre, European Commission, Ispra, Italy; Flechsig, M.; Jeanneret, F.; Maggi, M., Inst. for Environ./Sustainability, Joint Research Centre, European Commission, Ispra, Italy; Martens, P.; Menne, B.; Menzel, A., Lehrstuhl fuer Bioklimatologie, Technical University Munich, Munich, Germany; Sparks, T.","The analysis of changes in the timing of life cycle-events of organisms (phenology) has been able to contribute significantly to the assessment of potential impacts of climate change on ecology. These phenological responses of species to changes in climate are likely to have significant relevance for socio-economic issues such as agriculture, forestry and human health and have proven able to play a role in raising environmental awareness and education on climate change. This paper presents the European Phenology Network (EPN), which aims to increase the efficiency, added value and use of phenological monitoring and research, and to promote the practical use of phenological data in assessing the impact of global (climate) change and possible adaptation measures. The paper demonstrates that many disciplines have to deal with changes in the timing of life-cycle events in response to climate change and that many different user groups are involved. Furthermore, it shows how EPN addresses issues such as (1) raising public awareness and education, (2) the integration and cooperation of existing observing systems, (3) integration and access to phenological information and (4) communication.","Agriculture; Climate change; Communication; Ecology; Forestry; Human health","adaptation; agriculture; animal; article; climate; environmental monitoring; Europe; forestry; human; interpersonal communication; periodicity; public health; public relations; Adaptation, Physiological; Agriculture; Animals; Climate; Communication; Environmental Monitoring; Europe; Forestry; Humans; Interprofessional Relations; Periodicity; Public Health",,,,,,"Ahas, R., Long-term phyto-, ornitho- and ichthyophenological time-series analyses in Estonia (1999) Int J Biometeorol, 42, pp. 119-123; Ahmad, Q.K., Anisimov, O., (2001) Summary for Policymakers. Climate Change 2001: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability. A Report of Working Group II of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 17. , IPCC, Geneva; Beaubien, E.G., Freeland, H.J., Spring phenology trends in Alberta, Canada: Links to ocean temperature (2000) Int J Biometeorol, 44, pp. 53-59; Begon, M., Harper, J.L., Townsend, C.R., (1990) Ecology; Individuals, Populations and Communities, p. 945. , Blackwell, Boston; Bindi, M., Fibbi, L., Gozzini, B., Orlandini, S., Miglietta, F., Modelling the impact of future climate scenarios on yield and yield variability of grapevine (1996) Clim Res,